(177, 'REL Southwest''s EL and PreK Work Showcased at National Principals Conference', 'jwackwit', '2017-08-18', '', 'REL Southwest''s EL and PreK Work Showcased at National Principals Conference', 'REL Southwest hosted two sessions at the <a class="bold" href="http://www.principalsconference.org/home/">National Principals Conference</a> in Philadelphia on July 9&ndash;10, 2017. The sessions highlighted our work adapting early warning systems to identify at-risk English learner students and examining the alignment between early childhood evaluation instruments.', '', '2017-08-18', '', 0, 'AR, EL, TX, ', 0, 0, 'no', 'Early childhood/preK	English learners	', 'http://relsouthwest.sedl.org/news/items/2017-08-npc/npc-banner3.png', '2017 National Principals Conference Logo', 'Joni Wackwitz', '', '', '', '', '', 'REL Southwest showcases work at National @PrincipalsConf #NPC17', 'RELSouthwest, PrincipalsConf', 'pic.twitter.com/05adzEObCa', 'Website', 'REL Southwest EL and PreK Work Showcased at National Principals Conference', 'Sessions described how to adapt early warning systems for ELs and how to use crosswalks to compare preK evaluation instruments.', 'http://relsouthwest.sedl.org/news/items/2017-08-npc/npc-banner2.png', 'Regional Educational Laboratory program, REL program, REL, Regional Educational Laboratory Southwest, REL Southwest, REL SW, early warning systems, EL students, English learners, English language learners, ELLs, at risk students, at-risk English learners, at-risk ELLs, English language proficiency,  English Learners Research Alliance, Arkansas Teacher Excellence and Support System, Arkansas TESS, TESS, crosswalks, prekindergarten instruction, Early Childhood Environment Rating System, ECERS-3, Classroom Assessment Scoring System, preK assessments, preK evaluations, teacher evaluations,  Arkansas Prekindergarten Research Alliance, National Principals Conference, NPC, National Association of Elementary School Principals, National Association of Secondary School Principals, NAESP, NASSP', 'REL_Southwest_Hosts_PreK_and_EL_Sessions_at', '<div class="sidebar-rt">\r\n<p class="sidebar-title"><span class="darkgray">National Principals Conference</span></p>\r\n<p class="sidebar-text">Bringing together primary and secondary school leaders, the inaugural National Principals Conference explored the theme &ldquo;Connecting Great Leaders Across All Levels."</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>REL Southwest hosted two sessions at the <a class="bold" href="http://www.principalsconference.org/home/">National Principals Conference</a> in Philadelphia on July 9&ndash;10, 2017. The first highlighted our work assisting Texas districts in adapting early warning systems to identify at-risk English learner students. The second featured our work assisting Arkansas policymakers in developing a crosswalk to examine the alignment between three early childhood evaluation instruments.</p>\r\n<p class="subhead">Creating Early Warning System Indicators Specific to English Learners<br > <span class="datetime">July 9, 2017 | 9:00&ndash;10:15 a.m. ET</span></p>\r\n<p>Early warning systems use readily available data and research-based indicators to identify students at risk of missing key education milestones. Standard indicators used to flag off-track students include attendance, behavior, course performance, and on-time promotion. But additional indicators are often needed to accurately monitor specific student populations, such as English learners (ELs).</p>\r\n<img class="stat" src="http://relsouthwest.sedl.org/news/items/2017-08-npc/stat.png" alt="60 percent of ELs are not reclassified after firve or mor years in U.S. schools (Olsen, 2010)" width="175" >\r\n<p>In this interactive session, REL Southwest researchers <span class="darkgray">Ashley Simpson Baird, Ph.D.</span>, and <span class="darkgray">Montrischa M. Williams, Ph.D.</span>, described how to build or adapt early warning systems to identify at-risk EL students. As a real-world example, the researchers drew on REL Southwest&rsquo;s recent <a class="bold" href="http://relsouthwest.sedl.org/resources/tools_products/tools/ews-els/index.html">analytic technical support&nbsp;project</a> assisting three Texas school districts in adapting their early warning systems, a project done in collaboration with our <a class="bold" href="http://relsouthwest.sedl.org/research-alliances/english_learners.html">English Learners Research Alliance</a>. Approximately 30 school leaders, including counselors and principals, attended the session.</p>\r\n<p>Through a series of reflection exercises, participants considered indicators and outcomes that could help identify at-risk EL students in grades 1&ndash;12. After each exercise, the presenters shared relevant research as well as their experiences working with schools and districts. Using the Texas district data, the presenters then walked participants through the process of building or adapting an early warning system to target EL students. Participants received a template to guide this process. In closing, the group discussed how they might apply the process at their schools.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li class="dbltriangle"><a class="bold" href="http://relsouthwest.sedl.org/resources/tools_products/tools/ews-els/index.html"> View webinars and videos on this topic</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><img class="banner" src="http://relsouthwest.sedl.org/news/items/2017-08-npc/figure1a.png" alt="Figure title: Building an early warning system for EL students \r\n1. Gather and prepare student data \r\n2. Identify EL-specific indicators of risk to use \r\n3. Determine thresholds of risk for each indicator \r\n4. Conduct a hit rate analysis; \r\n\r\nSubtitle: EL-specific indicators \r\nSubcategory 1: Progress in first language\r\nindicator 1: Language 1 (L1) proficiency \r\nindicator 2: L1 literacy \r\nindicator 3: L1 math and science content-area knowledge; \r\n\r\nSubcategory 2: Progress in English\r\nindicator 1: Initial level on state English language proficiency assessments \r\nindicator 2: Progress in mastering core content: reading, writing, math \r\nindicator 3: Level of literacy at exit from EL services;	\r\n\r\nSubcategory 3: Student history\r\nindicator 1: Years in U.S. schools\r\nindicator 2: Participation in special EL programming \r\nindicator 3: Type of mobility (interstate, inter-district, international) \r\nindicator 4: Level of interrupted schooling" width="590" ></p>\r\n<p class="subhead">Alignment of the Arkansas Teacher Excellence and Support System to Other Measures of Prekindergarten Instructional and Classroom Quality<br > <span class="datetime">July 10, 2017 | 2:15&ndash;3:30 p.m. ET</span></p>\r\n<p>School leaders often need to determine how different standards, curricula, or evaluation tools align. One effective method for doing so is a crosswalk analysis. In this interactive session, <span class="darkgray">Angelica Herrera, Ph.D.</span>, REL Southwest researcher, and <span class="darkgray">Janice Keizer</span>, REL Southwest prekindergarten (preK) alliance liaison, described how to develop such a crosswalk.</p>\r\n<p>As a real-world example, the presenters shared a crosswalk that REL Southwest created to show how Arkansas&rsquo;s Teacher Excellence and Support System (TESS) aligns with two well-established preK evaluation tools: the Early Childhood Environment Rating System (ECERS-3) and the Classroom Assessment Scoring System (CLASS&trade;) PreK assessment. This project was done in collaboration with our <a class="bold" href="http://relsouthwest.sedl.org/research-alliances/arkansas_prek.html">Arkansas Prekindergarten Research Alliance</a>.</p>\r\n<p>To develop this crosswalk, REL Southwest reviewed the three instruments, comparing and contrasting their different elements. The team then created a matrix showing the alignment between TESS, ECERS&#8209;3, and CLASS in terms of domains, dimensions, and criteria measured. The goal was to inform Arkansas policymakers about TESS&rsquo;s potential as a measure of preK teacher performance.</p>\r\n<p style="margin-bottom: 20px;">The presenters walked participants through the process for developing a crosswalk, providing a series of examples. Participants then shared the preK evaluation tools their districts use and discussed their experiences with developing and using crosswalks. In closing, the presenters discussed the many types of documents and tools that can be compared using a crosswalk. For example, one participant shared how her district developed a crosswalk of special education curriculum and services.</p>\r\n<img class="banner" src="http://relsouthwest.sedl.org/news/items/2017-08-npc/figure2a.png" alt="Figure title: Developing an alignment crosswalk\r\n1. Evaluate the tools and documents for common terminology, teacher behaviors, and criteria\r\n2. Define acceptable degrees of alignment or match, such as complete match, partial match, and no match\r\n3.Review the tools or documents; for each domain, dimension, and criteria, record the degree of match in a matrix\r\n\r\nSubtitle: Tips for success	\r\nTip 1: Use only the information in the tools or documents to assign degree-of-match determinations\r\nTip 2: Guard against bias by using more than one reviewer; seek consensus among reviewers when they disagree" width="580" >\r\n<h2 class="gallery">Gallery</h2>\r\n<div class="grid-50 gallery-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 0;">\r\n<p><a href="http://relsouthwest.sedl.org/news/items/2017-08-npc/npc-p1.png"><img src="http://relsouthwest.sedl.org/news/items/2017-08-npc/npc-p1sm.png" alt="photo of Ashley Simpson Baird (left) and Montrischa M. Williams" ></a></p>\r\n<p>Presenters Ashley Simpson Baird, Ph.D.,&nbsp;(left) and Montrischa M. Williams, Ph.D.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="grid-50 gallery-box push-5">\r\n<p><a href="http://relsouthwest.sedl.org/news/items/2017-08-npc/npc-2.png"><img src="http://relsouthwest.sedl.org/news/items/2017-08-npc/npc-2sm.png" alt="photo of session participants" ></a></p>\r\n<p>Ses