 the projects. All of our projects spring from the research questions developed by alliance members.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>One of the topics that the alliance identified was investigating kindergarten entry assessment tools. Several states are using assessment tools to determine children&rsquo;s knowledge and skills at the beginning of kindergarten as this can help teachers know how to best support individual children at the start of school. New Mexico&rsquo;s Kindergarten Observation Tool (KOT) is one such assessment tool, and the Alliance was interested to <a href="https://ies.ed.gov/ncee/edlabs/projects/project.asp?projectID=4531">study the validity</a> of the KOT. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The KOT is an assessment that kindergarten teachers complete at the beginning of the school year. Teachers observe students as they engage in regular classroom activities during the first 30 days of school. Teachers then rate children on twenty-six indicators of children&rsquo;s competency. Teachers can then use the data to individualize instruction, supporting each child in the areas where they still have the most room to grow.</p>\r\n<p>The REL Southwest examined the data from the 2015 version of the KOT. Katie Dahlke, principal investigator and principal researcher for REL Southwest, explains, &ldquo;The study examined whether the tool is measuring the areas of knowledge and skill that it&rsquo;s intended to measure, and if not, what areas of knowledge and skill it was measuring.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>The study includes psychometric analysis of the KOT items, cognitive interviews with teachers, and inventories of other states&rsquo; kindergarten entry assessments. In addition, REL Southwest analyzed the correlation between the KOT and the Dynamic Indicators of Basic Early Literacy Skills (DIBELS) Next, another assessment of literacy skills.</p>\r\n<p>Research alliance members will be able to use the findings to determine appropriate uses of the KOT and to identify opportunities to improve the measure to better support New Mexico kindergarten teachers. REL Southwest&rsquo;s work also reaches beyond the alliance. Based on the methods used in the KOT study, Dahlke presented at the National Principals Conference about the evidence needed to determine if an early grades assessment is valid. Dahlke conducted a similar presentation at the New Mexico Coalition of Education Leaders Conference.</p>\r\n<p>Stakeholders have also validated the 2016 KOT which was administered statewide and also have completed standard setting for the 2016 KOT. Stakeholders are currently investigating the validity of the 2017 version of the KOT. &nbsp;As the New Mexico Public Education Department and the New Mexico Children, Youth, and Families Department continue to tweak the KOT, they recognize the importance of testing the validity of new versions. Dahlke notes, &ldquo;This shows New Mexico is committed to having a strong research base for their kindergarten entry assessment and its appropriate uses.&rdquo;</p>', '', '0000-00-00', '', 1, 'NM-PK, ', 1, 1, 'no', 'Early childhood/preK	', 'http://relsouthwest.sedl.org/common/images/newsroom/PreK-students.png', 'PreK students with teacher', 'Cora Goldston', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Pr-Kindergarten, Early Childhood Education, Kindergarten, REL Southwest ', 'Prekindergarten_Research_in_New_Mexico_Setting_a_Research', '', '', ''),
(187, 'American Institutes for Research Awarded REL&nbsp;Southwest Contract for 2017&ndash;22', 'jwackwit', '2017-11-28', '', 'American Institutes for Research Awarded REL&nbsp;Southwest Contract for 2017&ndash;22', 'We are excited to announce that American Institutes for Research has been awarded the new REL Southwest contract for 2017-2022.', '', '2017-11-29', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'no', 'Other	', 'http://relsouthwest.sedl.org/common/images/photos/relsw.png', 'Photo of field of wildflowers with REL Southwest logo and name overlaying it', 'Michael Vaden-Kiernan, Ph.D.', 'http://www.air.org/person/michael-vaden-kiernan', '', '', '', '', 'New @RELSouthwest contract for 2017-22 awarded to American Institutes for Research @Education_AIR @IESResearch', 'RELSouthwest, Education_AIR', 'pic.twitter.com/70Syd57k93', 'Website', 'American Institutes for Research Awarded 2017?22 REL Southwest Contract', 'The Regional Educational Laboratory (REL) Southwest assists Arkansas, Louisiana, New Mexico, Oklahoma, and Texas in using data and research evidence to address high-priority education needs.', 'http://relsouthwest.sedl.org/common/images/photos/relsw.png', 'Regional Educational Laboratory program, REL program, REL, Regional Educational Laboratory Southwest, REL Southwest, REL SW, American Institutes for Research, AIR, IES, Institute of Education Sciences', 'American_Institutes_for_Research_Awarded_New_REL_Southwest', '<p>We are excited to announce that <a href="http://www.air.org"><strong>American Institutes for Research</strong></a> has been awarded the <br >REL&nbsp;Southwest 2017&ndash;22 contract to serve the region of Arkansas, Louisiana, New Mexico, Oklahoma, and Texas. Our partners in this work include the state education agencies in our region as well as six subcontractors: Decision Information Resources, Empirical Education, Gibson Consulting, RAND, Safal Partners, and WestEd. This team includes skilled quantitative and qualitative researchers as well as staff with experience working with and supporting collaborative research partnerships with state education agencies and other stakeholders.</p>\r\n<p style="margin-bottom: 10px;"><span class="darkgray">We have six major REL Southwest research partnerships under development:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li class="yellowbox">Southwest College and Career Readiness (SWCCR) Research Partnership with the Arkansas&nbsp;Department of Education</li>\r\n<li class="yellowbox">Southwest Teacher Preparation and Professional Development (SWTPPD) Research Partnership with the Louisiana Department of Education</li>\r\n<li class="yellowbox">Southwest English Language Learners (SWELL) Research Partnership with the New Mexico Public Education Department</li>\r\n<li class="yellowbox">Southwest Early Childhood Education (SWECE) Research Partnership with the Oklahoma State Department of Education</li>\r\n<li class="yellowbox">Southwest School Improvement (SWSI) Research Partnership with the Texas&nbsp;Education Agency</li>\r\n<li class="yellowbox">Southwest Networked Improvement Community (SWNIC)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 6px;">Each of these major partnerships will result in innovative technical support, coaching, research, and dissemination activities that will increase knowledge in relevant content areas while informing current policy and practice. We look forward to engaging stakeholders in these and other partnerships to produce relevant and useful products.</p>\r\n<p>Best wishes during this holiday season and in the coming new year!</p>\r\n<p><strong>Visit our new website:</strong>&nbsp;<a href="https://ies.ed.gov/ncee/edlabs/regions/southwest/index.asp">https://ies.ed.gov/ncee/edlabs/regions/southwest/index.asp</a></p>', '<style type="text/css">\r\na.bold {\r\n	font-weight: bold;\r\n	}\r\na.bold2 {\r\n	font-weight: bold;\r\n	font-size: 13px;\r\n	}\r\ndiv p {\r\n	font-size: 13px;\r\n	line-height: 20px;\r\n	margin-bottom: 14px;\r\n	}\r\ndiv p.floater {\r\n	padding: 5px 0px 10px 20px;\r\n	float: 