(188, 'REL Southwest Hosts Workshops for Louisiana Charter School Educators', 'blitke', '2017-11-28', '', 'REL Southwest Hosts Workshops for Louisiana Charter School Educators', 'This fall, REL Southwest hosted two workshops to provide resources and strategies for Louisiana charter school educators. The events were conducted in partnership with the Greater New Orleans Collaborative of Charter Schools and the Louisiana Department of Education.', '', '2017-11-28', '', 0, 'LA, ', 0, 0, 'no', 'Charter schools	', '/news/items/2017-11/lawk-banner2.jpg', 'Photo of charter school students at their desks', 'Darlene Brown', 'http://relsouthwest.sedl.org/about/staff/darlene_brown.html', '', '', '', '', 'REL Southwest hosts workshops for Louisiana charter school educators', '', 'pic.twitter.com/wbV0BOmtu9', 'Website', 'REL Southwest Hosts Workshops for Louisiana Charter School Educators', '', '/news/items/2017-11/relhosts1.jpg', 'Regional Educational Laboratory program, REL program, REL, Regional Educational Laboratory Southwest, REL Southwest, REL SW, charter school, Louisiana Charter Schools Research Alliance, school choice, New Orleans charter schools, NOLA charter schools, Greater New Orleans Collaborative of Charter Schools, GNOCCS, Louisiana Department of Education, LDOE', 'REL_Southwest_Hosts_Louisiana_Charter_School_Events', '<p>This fall, the REL Southwest hosted two events to provide resources and strategies for Louisiana educators. The REL Southwest Louisiana Charter School Research alliance held the events in partnership with the Louisiana Charter Schools Research Alliance members and organizations, the Greater New Orleans Collaborative of Charter Schools (GNOCCS), and the Louisiana Department of Education (LDOE).</p>\r\n<p>The first event was a back-to-school event on August 3&ndash;4, 2017, at Edward Hynes Charter School in New Orleans, Louisiana. The professional development sessions aimed to increase the effectiveness of instructional personnel in the areas of special education and science and mathematics, while also addressing, nurturing, and protecting the social, emotional, and physical welfare of the students they serve.</p>\r\n<p>On August 3, approximately 450 participants consisting of alliance members, principals, and their school staff were on hand throughout the day. Approximately 175 participants attended on August 4. During this event, participants increased their working knowledge on the following topics:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li class="yellowbox">Research on Special Education in charter schools</li>\r\n<li class="yellowbox">Louisiana state policies regarding special education</li>\r\n<li class="yellowbox">Task-driven strategies to differentiate instruction and improve learning in mathematics.</li>\r\n<li class="yellowbox">New Louisiana Science Standards and practical methods for increasing knowledge, literacy, and competency in Science.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>These topics addressed reflected the priorities of the research alliance and were also a response to federal and state accountability requirements, instructional priorities, and state standards.</p>\r\n<p>On October 16&ndash;17, REL Southwest and partners GNOCCS and LDOE held a follow-up professional development workshop at the Orleans Parish School Board Office. The event focused on the New Louisiana Science Standards that were discussed at the back-to-school event. Forty-four science teachers were in attendance over the course of these two days. The presenter, Jean-May Brett, former LDOE Director of Science built on this summer&rsquo;s training by providing additional science instructional strategies.</p>\r\n<br style="clear: both;" >\r\n<div class="mobileFullwidth" style="background-color: #ebebeb; padding: 10px; margin-right: 20px; margin-bottom: 5px; width: 42%; float: left;">\r\n<p><img class="responsive" src="/news/items/2017-11/relhosts1.jpg" alt="Photo of some of the 450 conference participants consisting of alliance members, principals, and their school 